    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Jazz's Creation Myth</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marc Furstenberg letter about Apr 22 article on jazz hypothesizes about possible reasons for deliberately obscuring its origins (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Search of the Man Who May Have Created Jazz,'' by Michael Cieply [April 22]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Search of the Man Who May Have Created Jazz,'' by Michael Cieply [April 22]:</p>
        <p>The newspaperman Bat Masterson said he first heard jazz in Mamie Silk's Denver whorehouse in the 1880s. This squares with Jell Roll Morton's recollection in ''Mamie Desdume's Blues.'' Could this birth, on the wrong side of the bed, explain why jazz's origins may have been deliberately obscured?</p>
        <p>Marc Furstenberg  Manhattan</p>
        <p>BUDDY BOLDEN</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
